To be honest after baby 2 if you haven’t noticed I took a step back from blogging/“influencing”. Mainly because brands had no grace and had so many expectations and we’re not flexible when I just couldn’t do certain things because honestly I didn’t have the mental capacity and my body was still healing and IS still healing. I refused to overwork myself at the detriment of my family and my mental health to appease a company. Some people have been so understanding but for the ones that weren’t it really made me evaluate what I really want out of life. 

Just because people on IG make it look so easy to have kids it’s not. It’s a huge adjustment and inexplainable unless you’ve gone through it yourself. We are so desensitized to what women go through to bare children. 

If all you did was feed and care for your children today, that is enough. That is a whole job in itself. Please don’t let anyone ever make you think otherwise. 
 
In conclusion, men could never! 

Ps thank you to all the brands and people who get it and have been so lovely to work with 🙏🏾

Everyone talks about the pressure to bounce back physically after kids but what about the silent pressure to bounce back mentally? (Which is a longer recovery in my opinion) And the pressure to just jump back into life, like everything is the same. In all honesty, I don’t feel the same after having kids. What used to fill me no longer does. The type of life I thought I wanted is not that same vision anymore. And I’m still navigating exactly what I want and how it looks. All I know is, trying to jump back into things like I did before no longer serves me. I can look at it as negative but really I’m just evolving and that’s ok. Whatever it looks like for you, don’t feel bad or apologize for prioritizing yourself and your kids and DEFINITELY don’t feel bad for prioritizing your mental health. If there’s anything I’ve realized is that a lot of people won’t get it, even your extended family. But trust yourself. YOU get it, even if it doesn’t feel like it in the moment.  I’ve never grown as much in such a short amount of time, but becoming a mother does that to you. It’s a beautiful, challenging, and exhausting experience all at once. But this growth is unmatched. I love the person I’m becoming. 🙏🏾

When God says move, you move. We didn’t move under what seemed liked the greatest circumstances. We basically had to make a decision quick and fast. But instead of leaning into the anxiety and rushing, we waited on God’s timing. By the time it came to move, everything was so perfectly aligned we were 100% sure it was right. And now being here two months we are so much happier and lighter. Leaving the glamour of LA was hard, it’s definitely much cooler to say you live in LA but we chose true happiness over what “looks good” to others. Though we don’t plan on making this a permanent move, we are ready, willing and open to this new chapter until God moves us again ❤️

Getting your hair done is such a big part of being a black girl. It’s in all our core memories one way or another. Of all the things we want to break from our past, this is one tradition I love to keep. ❤️

My goal with my children is less about academic intelligence and more about emotional intelligence. The latter gets you a lot further in life. One thing I learned being a mom is that kids understand way more than we give them credit for. Even at a very young age. So many people ask me “how I did this or that” and my answer is always we started young. They might not get it right away and that’s ok but normalizing it young makes it so much easier when they’re older. Of course they are kids they are going to have their moments and there are things developmentally they are not able to do, but I still believe in showing them anyway and when you see the moment it clicks for them it’s so beautiful to know you are teaching them life skills they can take on to adulthood.

The results actually shocked me 👀 I’m not sure why everyone is putting socks in their head when Bantu knots reign tried and true. 💯 

All the products I used are in my august highlights and LTK. This will now be my go to no heat curl look 

On blow dried and flat ironed hair. Separate hair into 4 sections. Apply hair oil and setting lotion, comb thru, twist into bantu knot, secure with a satin scrunchie. Leave overnight and take out in the morning.

My morning Routine. #sponsored by @toms_of_maine With it being back to school time, the importance of keeping a morning routine has been crucial. I get up at 6 am and the first thing I do is meditate for 20 minutes. Then I journal for 20 minutes. After that I get up and make the bed, let the light in, and go to brush my teeth. I’ve been using Tom’s toothpaste for years because it has no unnecessary ingredients and the Luminous white toothpaste works so well to keep my teeth nice and white. Next, I shower and then do all my skincare and hair routines. I get dressed and then I put my deodorant on.  I love the smell of the Complete Protection deodorant in Rose + Vanilla and It’s also the only brand of deodorant I have worn for years. It has no aluminum, no parabens, and no artificial fragrances. Now that I’m ready for the day, I reset the house by letting light in and emptying the dishwasher. Then it’s time to get the girls ready for the day xx #tomsofmaine #naturaldeodorant #naturaltoothpaste #tomsofmainepartner
